@dhh at least we've answered the question "Who will mock the mockers?" Carry on.
@dhh I appreciate this discussion, either way. But one thing I think has made Rails successful is noobs walking into a testing culture.
@dhh Mocks don't for me. Too brittle & often just bake wrong assumptions into tests.
@dhh for me, speed is about development speed. Always. Tests help that almost always.
@dhh agree there too. I find it unhelpful to lump the concepts together. At Pivotal, for example, this was a big (and healthy) debate.
@dhh I'm with you. Tests don't need to be fast. It's great when they can be, but better to test reality & have easier to maintain tests.
@dhh the challenge is having the discipline to test after the fact and the rigor to make sure the tests will fail if the code does.
@dhh I think you can love TDD & admit that sometimes it's easier to write the code & then test it, for small values if code.
@dhh it may be helpful to decouple (pun intended) the discussion of TDD & mocking. You can hate mocks & love TDD.
